From: nix-wasm <eric@codebutler.com>
Date: Fri, 20 Jun 2026 00:00:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] wasm: futex_time64 split-arity fix (kernel 6-arg + host intercept for 4-arg callers)

__NR_futex_time64 (422) maps to the generic 6-arg sys_futex. Two callers use
different arg counts on wasm:
  - nix.wasm's musl pthread: calls with 6 args via __wasm_syscall_6 (correct)
  - glib's g_futex_simple: calls with 4 args via __wasm_syscall_4 (only
    uaddr, op, val, utime — FUTEX_WAIT/WAKE, which ignore uaddr2/val3)

The wasm call_indirect in each __wasm_syscall_N path dispatches with EXACTLY N
args through a strictly-typed indirect call; the kernel syscall table maps each
entry to exactly one function arity.  No single table entry can serve both.

Split the fix: keep sys_futex (6-arg) in syscall_table.c (so __wasm_syscall_6
from nix.wasm/musl works), and intercept the 4-arg path at the HOST level in
kernel-worker.js — when __wasm_syscall_4 is called with nr=422 the host shim
zero-pads uaddr2/val3 and forwards the call to vmlinux_instance.exports.
wasm_syscall_6 directly, bypassing the 4-arg call_indirect path entirely.
FUTEX_WAIT/WAKE ignore the two extra args, so the zero-pad is correct.

The kernel-side change vs. the earlier "SYSCALL_DEFINE4 trampoline" approach:
the trampoline in the table worked for glib but broke nix.wasm's 6-arg path;
this patch restores sys_futex for the kernel side. The kernel-worker.js shim
was added alongside this patch to cover glib.

Add the 4-arg prototype + implementation (sys_wasm32_futex) anyway — it is still
referenced by the .h declarations added here, and the implementation is correct
and useful as documentation even though it is not registered in the table.

(musl itself pads its own futex calls to 6 args; only glib's raw syscall() call
site uses 4 args, so the host intercept is narrowly scoped.)
--- a/arch/wasm/include/asm/syscalls_wasm32.h	2026-06-20 03:33:21.221143796 -0400
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/syscalls_wasm32.h	2026-06-20 03:33:34.791224508 -0400
@@ -34,6 +34,18 @@
 					   sc_arg_u64(nbytes),
 					   unsigned int flags);
 
+/*
+ * futex_time64 (__NR_futex_time64, 422) maps to the generic 6-arg sys_futex,
+ * but userspace (musl's syscall(), glib's g_futex_simple) invokes it with only
+ * 4 args (uaddr, op, val, utime) for FUTEX_WAIT/WAKE. On wasm the kernel's
+ * syscall trampoline (__wasm_syscall_4) dispatches through a strictly-typed
+ * call_indirect, so a 4-arg call landing on the 6-arg sys_futex traps with a
+ * function-signature mismatch. Provide a 4-arg wrapper that forwards to
+ * sys_futex with uaddr2=NULL, val3=0 (correct for WAIT/WAKE, which ignore them).
+ */
+asmlinkage long sys_wasm32_futex(u32 __user *uaddr, int op, u32 val,
+				 const struct __kernel_timespec __user *utime);
+
 #endif
 
 #endif /* _ASM_WASM_SYSCALLS_WASM32_H */
--- a/arch/wasm/kernel/sys_wasm32.c	2026-06-20 03:33:21.240143909 -0400
+++ b/arch/wasm/kernel/sys_wasm32.c	2026-06-20 03:34:01.811385699 -0400
@@ -52,3 +52,17 @@
 	return ksys_sync_file_range(fd, sc_arg_u64_glue(offset),
 				    sc_arg_u64_glue(nbytes), flags);
 }
+
+/*
+ * 4-arg futex_time64 trampoline (see syscalls_wasm32.h). userspace calls
+ * syscall(__NR_futex_time64, uaddr, op, val, utime) — only 4 args — for
+ * FUTEX_WAIT/WAKE, but the generic handler is the 6-arg sys_futex. wasm's
+ * strictly-typed call_indirect would trap on the arity mismatch, so dispatch
+ * lands here (the syscall_table override) and forwards the missing requeue
+ * args (uaddr2, val3) as zeros, which WAIT/WAKE ignore.
+ */
+SYSCALL_DEFINE4(wasm32_futex, u32 __user *, uaddr, int, op, u32, val,
+		const struct __kernel_timespec __user *, utime)
+{
+	return sys_futex(uaddr, op, val, utime, NULL, 0);
+}
--- a/arch/wasm/kernel/syscall_table.c	2026-06-20 03:33:21.261144034 -0400
+++ b/arch/wasm/kernel/syscall_table.c	2026-06-20 03:34:18.615486255 -0400
@@ -22,5 +22,12 @@
 	__SYSCALL(__NR_fadvise64_64, sys_wasm32_fadvise64_64)
 	__SYSCALL(__NR_fallocate, sys_wasm32_fallocate)
 	__SYSCALL(__NR_sync_file_range, sys_wasm32_sync_file_range)
+	/* __NR_futex_time64 (422): keep the generic 6-arg sys_futex here.
+	 * The host runtime (kernel-worker.js) intercepts 4-arg callers (glib's
+	 * g_futex_simple) via __wasm_syscall_4 and zero-pads them to 6 args
+	 * before forwarding to wasm_syscall_6, so the kernel always sees 6 args.
+	 * See also sys_wasm32_futex() in sys_wasm32.c (implementation kept for
+	 * reference, not registered in the table). */
+	__SYSCALL(__NR_futex_time64, sys_futex)
 #endif
 };
